v1.0_december_release Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that user can carry out a text based search against a class Purpose:
Test to ensure that a user can carry out a text based search against a class, and the system will return a set of results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1. Go to the search data page.
. check the check box corresponding to CLASS.
. Select the TEXT radio button.
. Enter a search item into the search field.
. Click on Search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. These results will contain the search item as a part or whole in the
class name or the description.
Verification Logic:
The search item will be present as a substring, or as a whole in the class name.

v1.0_december_release Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can carry out a text based search agianst teh attributes Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a text based search against the attributes and the system will return a set of results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1. Go to Search Data page.
. Check the check box corresponding to ATTRIBUTE.
. Select the TEXT radio button.
. Enter the search item into the search field.
. Click on Search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. The results may/may not contain the search item as a part or as a
whole of the class name.

erification Logic:
The system searches for the search item against the attribute list, and it returns the classes that contains the search item as a part or as a whole of its attribute name and description.
o in the results returned it is possible that we do not have any instance of the search item in the class names. So in such cases, the results returned can be verified by checking for the entries in the database, where the search item will be present as a part or whole in the attribute name or description of the returned classes .

o in the results returned it is possible that we do not have any instance of the search item (object name corresponding to the concept code) in the class names. So in such cases, the results returned can be verified by checking for the entries in the database, where the search item will be present in the concept code corresponding to the attribute list of the returned classes .

v1.0_december_release Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can enter multiple search items separated by space/s in the search field Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can search for multiple terms at one go by entering multiple search items in the search field delimited by space/s.
Setup:
Procedure:
1. Go to Search Data page.
. Check the check box corresponding to either CLASS or ATTRIBUTE.
. Select the radio button corresponding to either TEXT or CONCEPT CODE.
. Enter multiple search items (eg : item1 item2) separated by space/s in
the search field.
. Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. Some of the returned results will contain item1 as a part or whole in
the class name.
. Some of the returned results will contain item2 as a part or whole in
the class name.
Verification Logic:
If search items are separarted by space/s the system considers each search item individually, and searches them against the class or attribute depending on which check box is selected.
mongst the search results returned some results would contain only item1 as a part or whole of the class name. Some search results would contain item2 as apart or whole of the class name.

v1.0_december_release Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can carry out a text based search agaianst a class and attribute simultaneously Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a text based search against the class and attributes simultaneously, and the system will return a set of search results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1. Go to Search Data page.
. Check the check boxes corresponding to both CLASS and ATTRIBUTE.
. Select the radio button corresponding to CLASS.
. Enter a search item in the search field.
. Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of search results.
. Amongst the set of search results returned, some results would contain
the search item as a part or whole of the class name. Some results
would not contain the search item in the class name.
Verification Logic:
While the system searches in the class and attribute list simultaneously, the class names that contain the search item as a part or whole are returned. The classes which contain the search item as a part or whole in its attribute list are also returned. Theses classes may not have the search item in its class name, so these results have to be verified by checking for the entry in the database.

v1.0_december_release Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against class and attributes simultaneously Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against the class and attributes simultaneously, and the system will return a set of search results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1. Go to Search Data page.
. Check the check boxes corresponding to both CLASS and ATTRIBUTE.
. Select the radio button corresponding to CONCEPT CODE.
. Enter a search item in the search field.
. Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of search results.
. Amongst the set of search results returned, some results would contain
the object name corresponding to search item (which is a concept code)
as a part or whole of the class name. Some results would not contain
the object name corresponding to the search item in the class name.
Verification Logic:
While the system searches in the concept code list of the class and attribute simultaneously, the classes that contain the concept code in the class name as a part or whole are returned. The classes which contain concept code (search item) in the attribute concept code list are also returned. These classes may not have the object name (corresponding to search item) in its class name, so these results have to be verified by checking for the entry in the database.

v1.0_december_release Search View Search Results Test to ensure that clicking on any of the listed objects shows a description of that object. Purpose:
est to ensure that clicking on any of the listed objects shows a description of that object. This test case also applies for the objects from the “Related Data” column and the path.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Go to the "Choose Search Category" page.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results. The system navigates to "Add
Limits" page.
) Select a condition and click on "Add Limit".
) Click on "Next".
) System will navigate to the "Define Search Results View" page.
) Click on "Next".
) System navigates to the "View Search Results" page.
) Click on any object.

nput/Data:

xpected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" page.
) In the "Add Limits" page, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
class to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two classes with a appropriate path and clicking
on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results View"
page. Here the classes on which rule was set and the classes from the
path/paths chosen (to connect the two classes) are displayed alongwith
their definition.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
page.
) Here all those objects which satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" page are displayed.
) On clicking on any of these objects, the systems shows up a page which
has description of that object. Also adjacent to the object's
description is the "Related Data" column, which contains links to the
data which is related to this object.
) This test case is also applicable to the objects from the "Related
Data" column and the path.

erification Logic:
ll the data that is available for a particular object in the database
hould get displayed once the user clicks on that object in the "View Search Results" page.
n the "Related Data" column all those which have bidirectional association with our class of interest are shown. If a unidirectional assocition from our class of interest to other classes exists, then all such classes also become part of the "Related Data" column.
owever, if a unidirectional association from other classes to our class of interest exists, then such classes do not become part of the "Related Data" column.
or "Inter Model Associations" all those classes are listed which have bidirectional assocaition between our class of interest and them.

erification Logic:
or Example:
f the user searches for geneconnect.domain.gene with a rule: Identifier Less Than 21. Then in "View Search Results" page:
ath map = Paths: Gene
ow, say the user clicks on Gene 4, then the
ath map = Paths: Gene -> Gene 4
ow, if the user clicks on the class, geneconnect.domain.Protein then path map becomes : Paths: Gene -> Gene 4 -> Protein

v1.0_december_release Search Add Limits Test case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor. Purpose:
est case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Go to the search data page.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results.
) Add a condition/rule to any attribute.

through which he/she wants to connect the two classes.
) Click on OK.
0) In the DAG view, the user can choose AND or OR to set a condition
between the two classes.

nput/Data:
Expected Output:
) On clicking on any of the returned results, the system navigates to
the "Add Limits" page.
) In the "Add Limits" page, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
class to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG view.

between the two classes are displayed in the Ambiguity resolver page.
) In the Dag view the two classes get associated with all those paths
which the user had chosen from the Ambiguity resolver page.

erification Logic:
ccording to the logical operator (AND or OR), a condition/rule is set between the two classes.
For example:
f the user adds the following two limits:
) id less than 20 for edu.wustl.fe.Gene
) id equals "123" for edu.wustl.fe.GenBankAccession
Now, if the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator AND then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 and which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123
If the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator OR then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 or which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123

 2007-03-06 2007-03-06 BOTH
v1.0 feb iteration Search Add Limits Test case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor. Purpose:
est case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results.
) Add a condition/rule to any attribute.
) Click on Add Limit.
) In the DAG view, the user should press shift and then click on the
two classes which he/she wants to connect.
) Click on connect (Arrow Tool).
) In the "Ambiguity resolver" page, the user should click on the paths
through which he/she wants to connect the two classes.
0) Click on OK.
1) In the DAG view, the user can choose AND or OR to set a condition
between the two classes.

nput/Data:
Expected Output:
) On clicking on any of the returned results, the system navigates to
the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) When the user connects the two categories, then all the available
paths between the two categories are displayed in the Ambiguity
resolver page.
) In the Dag view the two categories get associated with all those paths
which the user had chosen from the Ambiguity resolver page.

erification Logic:
ccording to the logical operator (AND or OR), a condition/rule is set between the two classes.
For example:
f the user adds the following two limits:
) id less than 20 for edu.wustl.fe.Gene
) id equals "123" for edu.wustl.fe.GenBankAccession
Now, if the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator AND then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 and which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123
If the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator OR then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 or which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123

v1.0 feb iteration Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can enter multiple search items separated by space/s in the search field Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can search for multiple terms at one go by entering multiple search items in the search field delimited by space/s.
Setup:
Procedure:
1) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Check the check box corresponding to either "Category" or "Attribute".
) Select the radio button corresponding to either "Text" or "Concept
Code".
) Enter multiple search items (eg : item1 item2) separated by space/s in
the search field.
) Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. Some of the returned results will contain item1 as a part or whole in
the category name.
. Some of the returned results will contain item2 as a part or whole in
the category name.
Verification Logic:
If search items are separated by space/s the system considers each search item individually, and searches them against the category or attribute depending on which check box is selected.
mongst the search results returned some results would contain only item1 as a part or whole of the category name. Some search results would contain item2 as apart or whole of the category name.

v1.0 feb iteration Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against category and attributes simultaneously Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against the category and attributes simultaneously, and the system will return a set of search results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Check the check boxes corresponding to both "Category" and "Attribute".
) Select the radio button corresponding to "Concept Code".
) Enter a search item in the search field.
) Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of search results.
. Amongst the set of search results returned, some results would contain
the object name corresponding to search item (which is a concept code)
as a part or whole of the category name. Some results would not
contain the object name corresponding to the search item in the
category name.
Verification Logic:
While the system searches in the concept code list of the category and attribute simultaneously, the categories that contain the concept code in the category name as a part or whole are returned. The categories which contain concept code (search item) in the attribute concept code list are also returned. These categories may not have the object name (corresponding to search item) in its category name, so these results have to be verified by checking for the entry in the database.

est to ensure that clicking on any of the returned results should give a list of attributes. The number of attributes and the attribute names are specific for any given category.
Setup:

) Enter the search item in the search field.
) Click on "Search".
) Click on any of the returned results.

nput/Data:

Expected Output:
) On clicking on any of the returned results, the system navigates to
the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, attributes specific to that category are
displayed.
Verification Logic:
ategory is a collection of attributes from one or more classes from the same or different caGrid applications like caTissue, caArray, GeneConnect
very class is composed of attributes which define the class. The number of attributes for any particular class and the attribute names are specific for a class.
For example:
category fe.Gene is made up of attributes:
a) Chromosome Map
) Identifier
) Name
) Pubmed Count
) Summary
) Symbol

 2007-03-06 2007-03-06 BOTH
v1.0 feb iteration Search My Data List Summary Test to ensure that when the user clicks on the hyperlink in the ‘My Data List Summary’ panel then the system navigates to the ‘Data List’ tab and this data item is shown selected in the tree view and its description is shown. Purpose:Test to ensure that when the user clicks on the hyperlink in the ‘My Data List Summary’ panel then the system navigates to the ‘Data List’ tab and this data item is shown selected in the tree view and its description is shown.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results. The system navigates to "Add
Limits" tab.
) Enter a condition and click on "Add Limit".
) User can add one/more constraints in the DAG view.
) Two categories are connected using an arrow tool. If more than one
path is available to connect the two categories then an 'Ambiguity
resolver' page pops up. User can select one/more paths to connect
the two categories.
) Click on "Next".
) System will navigate to the "Define Search Results View" tab.
) Click on "Next".
0) System navigates to the "View Search Results" tab.
1) Click on one/several elements.
2) Click on 'Add to Data List'.
3) Click on specific element.
4) The system navigates to 'Result Details' page.
5) Click on 'Add To Data List'.
6) Click on any hyperlink in the 'My Data List Summary' panel.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their
corresponding list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two categories with a appropriate path and
clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search
Results View" tab. Here the classes on which rule was set are
displayed alongwith their description.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
tab.
) Here all those elements which have satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" tab are displayed.
) All those elements that are added to the 'Data List', are displayed
as hyperlinks in the 'My Data List Summary' panel.
) After clicking on any of the hyperlinks in the 'My Data List
Summary' panel, the system navigates to the 'Data List' tab.
) The element on which the user had clicked in the 'My Data List
Summary' panel of the 'View Search Results' tab is shown selected in
the tree view which is on left hand side in the 'Data List' tab.
0) The description of this element i.e attributes along with their
values are also displayed in the 'Data List' tab.

Verification Logic:

 2007-03-06 2007-03-06 BOTH
v1.0 feb iteration Search My Data List Summary Test to ensure that when the user starts a new search and adds data items to the data list then these new data items get added to the list of the data items that are already added in the ‘My Data List Summary’ panel in the previous search. Purpose: Test to ensure that when the user starts a new search and adds data items to the data list then these new data items get added to the list of the data items that are already added in the ‘My Data List Summary’ panel in the previous search.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results. The system navigates to "Add
Limits" tab.
) Enter a condition and click on "Add Limit".
) User can add one/more constraints in the DAG view.
) Two categories are connected using an arrow tool. If more than one
path is available to connect the two categories then an 'Ambiguity
resolver' page pops up. User can select one/more paths to connect
the two categories.
) Click on "Next".
) System will navigate to the "Define Search Results View" tab.
) Click on "Next".
0) System navigates to the "View Search Results" tab.
1) Click on one/several elements.
2) Click on 'Add to Data List'.
3) Click on specific element.
4) The system navigates to 'Result Details' page.
5) Click on 'Add To Data List'.
6) Click on 'Next'.
7) The system navigates to 'Data List' page.
8) The user can now start a new search by:
A) Clicking on 'Next', followed by clicking on 'Reset'.
A new search can now be started for which the above steps are to
be performed.
B) Clicking on previous in each tab till he/she reaches the 'Search
Dialog'.
C) Closing the 'Search Data' page. And then starting a new search by
clicking on the 'Search Data' button on the home page of caB2B
application.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their
corresponding list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two categories with a appropriate path and
clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search
Results View" tab. Here the classes on which rule was set are
displayed alongwith their description.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
tab.
) Here all those elements which have satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" tab are displayed.
) All those elements that are added to the 'Data List', are displayed
as hyperlinks in the 'My Data List Summary' panel.
) In the 'View Search Results' tab, clicking on 'Next', the system
navigates to 'Data List' tab.
) If the user clicks on 'Next' and then clicks on 'Reset', then the
system shows 'Search Dialog' in the 'Data List' tab. The user can
start a new search from here and add data items to the 'Data List'.
0) The user can start a new search by clicking on 'Previous' till he/she
reaches the 'Search Dialog'. He/she can then data items to the 'Data
List' by performing steps mentioned in 'Procedure'.
1) Another way to start a new search is to close the 'Search Data' page,
followed by clicking on the 'Search Data' button on the home page of
caB2B application. New data items can be added by performing the
steps mentioned in 'Procedure'.
2) Irrespective of the way in which the user adds these new data items
to the 'Data List', these new data items get added to the
previously added data items (which were added in the previous
search) in the 'My Data List Summary'.

Verification Logic:

 2007-03-06 2007-03-06 BOTH
v1.0 feb iteration Search View Search Results Test to ensure that clicking on any of the listed objects shows a description of that object. Purpose:
est to ensure that clicking on any of the listed objects shows a description of that object. This test case also applies for the objects from the “Related Data” column and the path.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Go to the "Choose Search Category" page.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results. The system navigates to "Add
Limits" page.
) Select a condition and click on "Add Limit".
) Click on "Next".
) System will navigate to the "Define Search Results View" page.
) Click on "Next".
) System navigates to the "View Search Results" page.
) Click on any object.

nput/Data:

xpected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" page.
) In the "Add Limits" page, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
class to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two classes with a appropriate path and clicking
on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results View"
page. Here the classes on which rule was set and the classes from the
path/paths chosen (to connect the two classes) are displayed alongwith
their definition.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
page.
) Here all those objects which satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" page are displayed.
) On clicking on any of these objects, the systems shows up a page which
has description of that object. Also adjacent to the object's
description is the "Related Data" column, which contains links to the
data which is related to this object.
) This test case is also applicable to the objects from the "Related
Data" column and the path.

erification Logic:
ll the data that is available for a particular object in the database
hould get displayed once the user clicks on that object in the "View Search Results" page.
n the "Related Data" column all those which have bidirectional association with our class of interest are shown. If a unidirectional assocition from our class of interest to other classes exists, then all such classes also become part of the "Related Data" column.
owever, if a unidirectional association from other classes to our class of interest exists, then such classes do not become part of the "Related Data" column.
or "Inter Model Associations" all those classes are listed which have bidirectional assocaition between our class of interest and them.

) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" page.
) In the "Add Limits" page, a set of attributes with their
corresponding list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
class to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two classes with a appropriate path and clicking
on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results View"
page. Here the classes on which rule was set and the classes from the
path/paths chosen (to connect the two classes) are displayed
alongwith their definition.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
page.
) Here all those objects which satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" page are displayed.
) On clicking on any of these objects, the systems shows up a page
which has description of that object. Also adjacent to the object's
description is the "Related Data" column, which contains classes
which are related to this object.
) Clicking on any of these classes would return a page which would
contain objects of that class.
) Clicking on any of these objects shows up a page which contains
description of this new object.
0) As the user navigates through all these different objects and
classes, a path map, "Paths" is shown, at every step, which contains
the path which the user traversed.
1) If the user clicks on any of the links in the path map then the
system navigates to the corresponding page.

erification Logic:
f the user searches for geneconnect.domain.gene with a rule: Identifier Less Than 21. Then in "View Search Results" page:
ath map = Paths: Gene
ow, say the user clicks on Gene 4, then the
ath map = Paths: Gene -> Gene 4
ow, if the user clicks on the class, geneconnect.domain.Protein then path map becomes : Paths: Gene -> Gene 4 -> Protein
ow, if the user clicks on object, Protein 7, then the path becomes: Paths: Gene -> Gene 4 -> Protein -> Protein 7
Now, for eg., in the path map if the user clicks on Gene 4 then the system should navigate to the object, Gene 4, and display its description and "Related Data".

) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators and edit boxes is displayed.
) Here the user adds multiple limits on a particular category/class.
Clicking on "Add Limit" that particular category/class gets registered
in the DAG view.
) Clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results
View" tab.
) Clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "View Search Results"
tab. Here the system displays results which have satisfied the
conditions imposed in the "Add Limits" tab.

v1.0 feb iteration Search End to end test cases Test to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via a single path chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results. Purpose:
est to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via a single path chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results.
Setup:
he queries should be imposed upon such 2 categories/classes which have multiple paths connecting them.
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search term in the search field.
) Click on "Search" button.
) Click on any one of the returned results.
) Enter an appropriate condition and click on "Add Limit" button.
) In similar manner register one more category/class in the DAG view.
) Click on the 2 categories/classes with the "Shift" button pressed.
) Click on the Arrow Tool.
0) Select only a single path from the "Ambiguity Resolver" to connect
the 2 categories/classes.
1) Specify the logical operator i.e. AND/OR to be used.
2) Click on "Next".
3) In the "Define Search Results View", click on "Next".
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute of a category/class, then
that particular category/class to which this attribute belongs,
gets registered in the DAG view. By performing above steps user can
add one more category/class to the DAG view.
) Since there are multiple paths available between the the two
categories/classes therefore an "Ambiguity Resolver" page pops up.
) The two categories/classes will be linked to each other with a path
chosen from the "Ambiguity Resolver".
) Clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results
View".
) Here the user can customize the result view. The user can specify
the category/class to be shown in the result view. To achieve this,
user can select the desired category/class from the "Select Deafult
View" drop down list.
) Click on "Next" to view the results.

) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.

Expected Output:

view.
) The source and the destination categories are connected with the help
of Arrow Tool or by clicking on the 'Auto Connect' button.
) Arrow Tool:
If no path is available between the source and the destination
categories then a "Connect Nodes Warning" dialog box pops up
showing a message "No path available/selected between source and
destination categories"
) Auto Connect:
If no path is available between the source and the destination
categories then a "Auto Connect Warning" dialog box pops up
showing a message "No curated path available between selected nodes"

) In the "Ambiguity resolver" page, the user should click on the paths
through which he/she wants to connect the two classes.
0) Click on OK.
1) In the DAG view, the user can choose AND or OR to set a condition
between the two classes.

nput/Data:
Expected Output:
) On clicking on any of the returned results, the system navigates to
the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) When the user connects the two categories, then all the available
paths between the two categories are displayed in the Ambiguity
resolver page.
) In the Dag view the two categories get associated with all those paths
which the user had chosen from the Ambiguity resolver page.

erification Logic:
ccording to the logical operator (AND or OR), a condition/rule is set between the two classes.
For example:
f the user adds the following two limits:
) id less than 20 for edu.wustl.fe.Gene
) id equals "123" for edu.wustl.fe.GenBankAccession
Now, if the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator AND then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 and which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123
If the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator OR then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 or which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123

v1.0_June_Release Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against category and attributes simultaneously Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against the category and attributes simultaneously, and the system will return a set of search results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Check the check boxes corresponding to both "Category" and "Attribute".
) Select the radio button corresponding to "Concept Code".
) Enter a search item in the search field.
) Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of search results.
. Amongst the set of search results returned, some results would contain
the object name corresponding to search item (which is a concept code)
as a part or whole of the category name. Some results would not
contain the object name corresponding to the search item in the
category name.
Verification Logic:
While the system searches in the concept code list of the category and attribute simultaneously, the categories that contain the concept code in the category name as a part or whole are returned. The categories which contain concept code (search item) in the attribute concept code list are also returned. These categories may not have the object name (corresponding to search item) in its category name, so these results have to be verified by checking for the entry in the database.

v1.0_June_Release Search End to end test cases Test to ensure that upon firing a query, the system returns results from all instances of the application. Purpose:
est to ensure that upon firing a query, the system returns results from all instances of the application.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search term in the search field.
) Click on "Search" button.
) Click on any one of the returned results.
) Enter an appropriate condition and click on "Add Limit" button.
) In similar manner register one more category/class in the DAG view.
) Click on the 2 categories/classes with the "Shift" button pressed.
) Click on the Arrow Tool.
0) Specify the logical operator i.e. AND/OR to be used.
1) Click on "Next".
2) In the "Define Search Results View", click on "Next".
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search" button, the system returns results. On clicking on any of
the returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute of a category/class, then
that particular category/class to which this attribute belongs,
gets registered in the DAG view. By performing above steps user can
add one more category/class to the DAG view.
) After clicking on the "Arrow tool" button, the two categories/classes
get connected with the only path connecting the two categories/classes.
) Clicking on the "Next" button, the system navigates to the "Define
Search Results View" tab.
) All those categories/classes are listed in the "Select Default View"
drop down which were added in the DAG view.
) Here the user can customize the result view. The user can specify
the category/class to be shown in the result view. To achieve this,
user can select the desired category/class from the "Select Deafult
View" drop down list.
) Click on "Next" to view the results.
) The system returns only those results which satisfy the conditions
imposed in the "Add Limits" tab.
0)That category/class which is chosen in the "Select Deafult View",the
elements of those particular category/class only are returned.
1) Here the user is able to view the relevant data from all the instances
of the application.
Verification Logic:

v1.0_June_Release Search End to end test cases Test to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via multiple paths chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results. Purpose:
est to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via multiple paths chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results.

etup:
he queries should be imposed upon such 2 categories/classes which have multiple paths connecting them.
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search term in the search field.
) Click on "Search" button.
) Click on any one of the returned results.
) Enter an appropriate condition and click on "Add Limit" button.
) In similar manner register one more category/class in the DAG view.
) Click on the 2 categories/classes with the "Shift" button pressed.
) Click on the Arrow Tool.
0) Select only multiple paths from the "Ambiguity Resolver" to connect
the 2 categories/classes.
1) Specify the logical operator i.e. AND/OR to be used.
2) Click on "Next".
3) In the "Define Search Results View", click on "Next".
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators and edit boxes is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute of a category/class, then
that particular category/class to which this attribute belongs,
gets registered in the DAG view. By performing above steps user can
add one more category/class to the DAG view.
) Since there are multiple paths available between the two
categories/classes therefore an "Ambiguity Resolver" page pops up.
) The two categories/classes will be linked to each other with all those
paths chosen from the "Ambiguity Resolver".
) Clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results
View".
) All those categories/classes are listed in the "Select Default View"
drop down which were added in the DAG view.
) Here the user can customize the result view. The user can specify
the category/class to be shown in the result view. To achieve this,
user can select the desired category/class from the "Select Deafult
View" drop down list.
) Click on "Next" to view the results.
) The system returns only those results which satisfy the conditions
imposed in the "Add Limits" tab.
0)That category/class which is chosen in the "Select Deafult View",the
elements of those particular category/class only are returned.

path is available to connect the two categories then an 'Ambiguity
resolver' page pops up. User can select one/more paths to connect

category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two categories with a appropriate path and
clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search
Results View" tab. Here the classes on which rule was set are

hould get displayed once the user clicks on that object in the "View Search Results" page.
n the "Related Data" column all those which have bidirectional association with our class of interest are shown. If a unidirectional assocition from our class of interest to other classes exists, then all such classes also become part of the "Related Data" column.
owever, if a unidirectional association from other classes to our class of interest exists, then such classes do not become part of the "Related Data" column.
or "Inter Model Associations" all those classes are listed which have bidirectional assocaition between our class of interest and them.

view.

of Arrow Tool or if a curated path is available then by clicking on
the 'Auto Connect' button.
) Suppose 2 categories are added in the DAG:
a) If the categories are not connected then in the yellow status bar
situated at the bottom of the DAG view shows:
Current expression: Expressions 1, 2 are not connected.
b) If the categories are connected with a logical AND operator then in
the yellow status bar situated at the bottom of the DAG view shows:
Current expression: ([1]AND[2])
c) If the categories are connected with a logical OR operator then in
the yellow status bar situated at the bottom of the DAG view shows:
Current expression: ([1]OR[2])

 2007-06-26 2007-06-26 BOTH
V1.1_July_Release Search Add Limits Test case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor. Purpose:
est case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results.
) Add a condition/rule to any attribute.
) Click on Add Limit.
) In the DAG view, the user should press shift and then click on the
two classes which he/she wants to connect.
) Click on connect (Arrow Tool).
) In the "Ambiguity resolver" page, the user should click on the paths
through which he/she wants to connect the two classes.
0) Click on OK.
1) In the DAG view, the user can choose AND or OR to set a condition
between the two classes.

nput/Data:
Expected Output:
) On clicking on any of the returned results, the system navigates to
the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) When the user connects the two categories, then all the available
paths between the two categories are displayed in the Ambiguity
resolver page.
) In the Dag view the two categories get associated with all those paths
which the user had chosen from the Ambiguity resolver page.

erification Logic:
ccording to the logical operator (AND or OR), a condition/rule is set between the two classes.
For example:
f the user adds the following two limits:
) id less than 20 for edu.wustl.fe.Gene
) id equals "123" for edu.wustl.fe.GenBankAccession
Now, if the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator AND then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 and which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123
If the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator OR then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 or which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123

V1.1_July_Release Search Data List Test to ensure that a new project gets added in the selected folder from ‘My Projects’, when the user adds a project using ‘Add New’ option in the create new experiment page. Purpose:
est to ensure that a new project gets added in the selected folder from ‘My Projects’, when the user adds a project using ‘Add New’ option in the create new experiment page.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Go to the "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on "Search".
) Click on any of the returned results. The system navigates to "Add
Limits" tab.
) Select a condition and click on "Add Limit".
) Click on "Next".
) System will navigate to the "Define Search Results View" tab.
) Click on "Next".
) System navigates to the "View Search Results" tab.
) Add few elements to the data list. For this click on one/more
elements, then click on "Add To Data List".
0) Click on "Next" button.
1) In the 'Data List' page, click on the 'Save Data List'.
2) Enter the title for the Data List
3) Click on 'Save' button.
4) Click on the 'Add to Experiment' button
5) Enter the title in the Experiment's name field.
6) Select an appropriate folder or create a new folder using 'Add New'
option.
7) Click on 'Save' button.
8) Close the Search Data window.
9) Click on the 'Experiment' tab.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" page.
) In the "Add Limits" page, a set of attributes with their
corresponding list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
class to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two classes with a appropriate path and clicking
on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results View"
page. Here the classes on which rule was set and the classes from the
path/paths chosen (to connect the two classes) are displayed
alongwith their definition.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
page.
) Here all those objects which satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" page are displayed.
) User can add one/more elements to the Data List.
) In "View Search Results" tab, clicking on "Next" button, the system
navigates to the "Data List" tab.
) In the "Data List" tab, clicking on any element, shows desription of
that element i.e. attributes along with their values
0) Clicking on 'Save Data List' button, a Save Data List window pops
up. After entering the title for the Data List and clicking on Save,
the data list gets saved and a success message is displayed at the
bottom of the page.
1) Clicking on 'Add to Experiment' button, a 'Create New Experiment'
page appears.
2) Clicking on 'Add New' adds a node in the 'My Projects'.
3) Typing the project name and hitting enter adds the project title
in 'My Projects'.
4) After saving the Experiment, a success message is displayed at the
bottom of the page.
5) After clicking on the 'Experiment' tab, all the parent projects are
displayed.
6) Double clicking on the project shows experiments and sub projects
under it.
Verification Logic:

V1.1_July_Release Search End to end test cases Test to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via multiple paths chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results. Purpose:
est to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via multiple paths chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results.

etup:
he queries should be imposed upon such 2 categories/classes which have multiple paths connecting them.
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search term in the search field.
) Click on "Search" button.
) Click on any one of the returned results.
) Enter an appropriate condition and click on "Add Limit" button.
) In similar manner register one more category/class in the DAG view.
) Click on the 2 categories/classes with the "Shift" button pressed.
) Click on the Arrow Tool.
0) Select only multiple paths from the "Ambiguity Resolver" to connect
the 2 categories/classes.
1) Specify the logical operator i.e. AND/OR to be used.
2) Click on "Next".
3) In the "Define Search Results View", click on "Next".
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators and edit boxes is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute of a category/class, then
that particular category/class to which this attribute belongs,
gets registered in the DAG view. By performing above steps user can
add one more category/class to the DAG view.
) Since there are multiple paths available between the two
categories/classes therefore an "Ambiguity Resolver" page pops up.
) The two categories/classes will be linked to each other with all those
paths chosen from the "Ambiguity Resolver".
) Clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results
View".
) All those categories/classes are listed in the "Select Default View"
drop down which were added in the DAG view.
) Here the user can customize the result view. The user can specify
the category/class to be shown in the result view. To achieve this,
user can select the desired category/class from the "Select Deafult
View" drop down list.
) Click on "Next" to view the results.
) The system returns only those results which satisfy the conditions
imposed in the "Add Limits" tab.
0)That category/class which is chosen in the "Select Deafult View",the
elements of those particular category/class only are returned.
Verification Logic:
 2007-06-26 2007-06-26 BOTH

) Clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results

page. Here the classes on which rule was set and the classes from the
path/paths chosen (to connect the two classes) are displayed
alongwith their definition.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
page.
) Here all those objects which satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" page are displayed.
) User can add one/more elements to the Data List.
) In "View Search Results" tab, clicking on "Next" button, the system
navigates to the "Data List" tab.
) In the "Data List" tab, clicking on any element, shows desription of
that element i.e. attributes along with their values
0) Clicking on 'Save Data List' button, a Save Data List window pops
up. After entering the title for the Data List and clicking on Save,
the data list gets saved and a success message is displayed at the
bottom of the page.
1) After saving the Experiment, a success message is displayed at the
bottom of the page.
2) After clicking on the 'Experiment' tab, all the parent projects are
displayed.
3) Double clicking on the project shows experiments and sub projects
under it. The experiment that was saved under this project is
listed here.
4) Clicking on the Experiment name in the LHS i.e. in 'My Projects'
shows the title, created date, last updated date and description of
the experiment in RHS.
5) On clicking on the hyperlink for experiment's name, in the LHS
Experiment Data Categories are listed i.e. LHS displays names of all
the categories/classes (that were added in the data list). The first
category name is shown selected is LHS and in the RHS all the
elements (attributes along with their values) pertaining to this
category which were added in the data list are shown.

V1.1_July_Release Search View Search Results Test to ensure that a path gets displayed as the user navigates to different objects. Purpose:
est to ensure that a path gets displayed as the user navigates to different objects.

etup:
Procedure:
) Go to the "Choose Search Category" page.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results. The system navigates to "Add
Limits" page.
) Select a condition and click on "Add Limit".
) Click on "Next".
) System will navigate to the "Define Search Results View" page.
) Click on "Next".
) System navigates to the "View Search Results" page.
) Click on any object.
0) Click on any of the classes from the "Related Data" column.
1) Click on any of the objects.

nput/Data:

xpected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" page.
) In the "Add Limits" page, a set of attributes with their
corresponding list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
class to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two classes with a appropriate path and clicking
on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results View"
page. Here the classes on which rule was set and the classes from the
path/paths chosen (to connect the two classes) are displayed
alongwith their definition.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
page.
) Here all those objects which satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" page are displayed.
) On clicking on any of these objects, the systems shows up a page
which has description of that object. Also adjacent to the object's
description is the "Related Data" column, which contains classes
which are related to this object.
) Clicking on any of these classes would return a page which would
contain objects of that class.
) Clicking on any of these objects shows up a page which contains
description of this new object.
0) As the user navigates through all these different objects and
classes, a path map, "Paths" is shown, at every step, which contains
the path which the user traversed.

erification Logic:
or Example:
f the user searches for geneconnect.domain.gene with a rule: Identifier Less Than 21. Then in "View Search Results" page:
ath map = Paths: Gene
ow, say the user clicks on Gene 4, then the
ath map = Paths: Gene -> Gene 4
ow, if the user clicks on the class, geneconnect.domain.Protein then path map becomes : Paths: Gene -> Gene 4 -> Protein
ow, if the user clicks on object, Protein 7, then the path becomes: Paths: Gene -> Gene 4 -> Protein -> Protein 7

bottom of the page. A set of 5 pages (maximum)is displayed at the
bottom of the "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Clicking on the page numbers will naviagte to the corresponding page.

) Clicking on "<<", the system navigates to the previous set of 5 pages.
) Clicking on ">>", the system navigates to the next set of 5 pages.
) Clicking on "<", the system navigates to the previous page.
) Clicking on ">", the system navigates to the next page.
) On the first page the arrow links corresponding to previous set and
previous page will be disabled.
0) On the last page the arrow links corresponding to the next set and
next page will be disabled.

|

erification Logic:
ll the data that is available for a particular object in the database
hould get displayed once the user clicks on that object in the "View Search Results" page.
n the "Related Data" column all those which have bidirectional association with our class of interest are shown. If a unidirectional assocition from our class of interest to other classes exists, then all such classes also become part of the "Related Data" column.
owever, if a unidirectional association from other classes to our class of interest exists, then such classes do not become part of the "Related Data" column.
or "Inter Model Associations" all those classes are listed which have bidirectional assocaition between our class of interest and them.

 2007-11-29 2007-11-29 BOTH
v2.0 Search Add Limits Test case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor. Purpose:
est case to ensure that the two classes are connected via appropriate logical opeartor.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on Search.
) Click on any of the returned results.
) Add a condition/rule to any attribute.
) Click on Add Limit.
) In the DAG view, the user should press shift and then click on the
two classes which he/she wants to connect.
) Click on connect (Arrow Tool).
) In the "Ambiguity resolver" page, the user should click on the paths
through which he/she wants to connect the two classes.
0) Click on OK.
1) In the DAG view, the user can choose AND or OR to set a condition
between the two classes.

nput/Data:
Expected Output:
) On clicking on any of the returned results, the system navigates to
the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) When the user connects the two categories, then all the available
paths between the two categories are displayed in the Ambiguity
resolver page.
) In the Dag view the two categories get associated with all those paths
which the user had chosen from the Ambiguity resolver page.

erification Logic:
ccording to the logical operator (AND or OR), a condition/rule is set between the two classes.
For example:
f the user adds the following two limits:
) id less than 20 for edu.wustl.fe.Gene
) id equals "123" for edu.wustl.fe.GenBankAccession
Now, if the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator AND then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 and which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123
If the user connects the above two classes (Gene and GenBankAccession) with a logical operator OR then the query would mean:
et all the FE Genes which have id less than 20 or which have GenBank Accesion id equal to 123

Setup:
Procedure:
1. Start the caB2B admin Application by opening the link.
. Select the Create category link from the Search data tab.
. Expand the Advance Search Option.
. Select the Text Option Button.
. Select the Attribute check box available.
. Type in the search term in the Search Box.

nput/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. The results may/may not contain the search item as a part or as a
whole of the category name.
. The search term must be present in one of the attribute names.
Verification Logic:
The system searches for the search item against the attribute list, and it returns the categories that contains the search item as a part or as a whole of its attribute name and description.
o in the results returned it is possible that we do not have any instance of the search item in the class names. So in such cases, the results returned can be verified by checking for the entries in the database, where the search item will be present as a part or whole in the attribute name or description of the returned categories.

) Select the radio button corresponding to either "Text" or "Concept
Code".
) Enter multiple search items (eg : item1 item2) separated by space/s in
the search field.
) Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. Some of the returned results will contain item1 as a part or whole in
the category name.
. Some of the returned results will contain item2 as a part or whole in
the category name.
Verification Logic:
If search items are separated by space/s the system considers each search item individually, and searches them against the category or attribute depending on which check box is selected.
mongst the search results returned some results would contain only item1 as a part or whole of the category name. Some search results would contain item2 as apart or whole of the category name.

v2.0 Search Advanced Search Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against category and attributes simultaneously Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against the category and attributes simultaneously, and the system will return a set of search results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Check the check boxes corresponding to both "Category" and "Attribute".
) Select the radio button corresponding to "Concept Code".
) Enter a search item in the search field.
) Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of search results.
. Amongst the set of search results returned, some results would contain
the object name corresponding to search item (which is a concept code)
as a part or whole of the category name. Some results would not
contain the object name corresponding to the search item in the
category name.
Verification Logic:
While the system searches in the concept code list of the category and attribute simultaneously, the categories that contain the concept code in the category name as a part or whole are returned. The categories which contain concept code (search item) in the attribute concept code list are also returned. These categories may not have the object name (corresponding to search item) in its category name, so these results have to be verified by checking for the entry in the database.

d) Less than or Equals
e) Greater than
f) Greater than or Equals
g) Between

i) Is Not Null

v2.0 Search End to end test cases Test to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected without a path chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results. Purpose:
est to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected without a path chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results.
Setup:
wo categories/classes should be selected which have a single path connecting them.
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search term in the search field.
) Click on "Search" button.
) Click on any one of the returned results.
) Enter an appropriate condition and click on "Add Limit" button.
) In similar manner register one more category/class in the DAG view.
) Click on the 2 categories/classes with the "Shift" button pressed.
) Click on the Arrow Tool.
0) Specify the logical operator i.e. AND/OR to be used.
1) Click on "Next".
2) In the "Define Search Results View", click on "Next".
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search" button, the system returns results. On clicking on any of
the returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute of a DEG, then that
particular category/class to which this attribute belongs,
gets registered in the DAG view. By performing above steps user can
add one more category/class to the DAG view.
) After clicking on the "Arrow tool", the two categories/classes get
connected with the only path connecting the two categories/classes.
) Clicking on "Next" button, the system navigates to the "Define Search
Results View" tab.
) Click on "Next" to view the results.
) The system returns only those results which satisfy the conditions
imposed in the "Add Limits" tab.

v2.0 Search End to end test cases Test to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via multiple paths chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results. Purpose:
est to ensure that when the two categories/classes are connected via multiple paths chosen from the “Ambiguity resolver” page, the system returns relevant results.

etup:
he queries should be imposed upon such 2 categories/classes which have multiple paths connecting them.
Procedure:
) Click on "Search Data" button on the home page of caB2B application.
) System navigates to "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search term in the search field.
) Click on "Search" button.
) Click on any one of the returned results.
) Enter an appropriate condition and click on "Add Limit" button.
) In similar manner register one more category/class in the DAG view.
) Click on the 2 categories/classes with the "Shift" button pressed.
) Click on the Arrow Tool.
0) Select only multiple paths from the "Ambiguity Resolver" to connect
the 2 categories/classes.
1) Specify the logical operator i.e. AND/OR to be used.
2) Click on "Next".
3) In the "Define Search Results View", click on "Next".
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their corresponding
list of operators and edit boxes is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute of a category/class, then
that particular category/class to which this attribute belongs,
gets registered in the DAG view. By performing above steps user can
add one more category/class to the DAG view.
) Since there are multiple paths available between the two
categories/classes therefore an "Ambiguity Resolver" page pops up.
) The two categories/classes will be linked to each other with all those
paths chosen from the "Ambiguity Resolver".
) Clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results
View".
) All those categories/classes are listed in the "Select Default View"
drop down which were added in the DAG view.
) Here the user can customize the result view. The user can specify
the category/class to be shown in the result view. To achieve this,
user can select the desired category/class from the "Select Deafult
View" drop down list.
) Click on "Next" to view the results.
) The system returns only those results which satisfy the conditions
imposed in the "Add Limits" tab.
0)That category/class which is chosen in the "Select Deafult View",the
elements of those particular category/class only are returned.

v2.0 Search Experiment Test to ensure that after clicking on the ‘Experiment’ tab all the added parent projects are displayed in the ‘My Projects’ folder. Purpose:
est to ensure that after clicking on the ‘Experiment’ tab all the added parent projects are displayed in the ‘My Projects’ folder.
Setup:
Procedure:
) Go to the "Choose Search Category" tab.
) Enter the search item in the search field. Click on "Search".
) Click on any of the returned results. The system navigates to "Add
Limits" tab.
) Select a condition and click on "Add Limit".
) Click on "Next".
) System will navigate to the "Define Search Results View" tab.
) Click on "Next".
) System navigates to the "View Search Results" tab.
) Add few elements to the data list. For this click on one/more
elements, then click on "Add To Data List".
0) Click on "Next" button.
1) In the 'Data List' page, click on the 'Save Data List'.
2) Enter the title for the Data List
3) Click on 'Save' button.
4) Click on the 'Add to Experiment' button
5) Enter the title in the Experiment's name field.
6) Select an appropriate folder or create a new folder using 'Add New'
option.
7) Click on 'Save' button.
8) Close the Search Data window.
9) Click on the 'Experiment' tab.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
) After entering a search item in the search field, followed by click
on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" page.
) In the "Add Limits" page, a set of attributes with their
corresponding list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
class to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.
) After connecting the two classes with a appropriate path and clicking
on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search Results View"
page. Here the classes on which rule was set and the classes from the
path/paths chosen (to connect the two classes) are displayed
alongwith their definition.
) On clicking on "Next", the system navigates to "View Search Results"
page.
) Here all those objects which satisfied the criteria applied in
the "Add Limits" page are displayed.
) User can add one/more elements to the Data List.
) In "View Search Results" tab, clicking on "Next" button, the system
navigates to the "Data List" tab.
) In the "Data List" tab, clicking on any element, shows desription of
that element i.e. attributes along with their values
0) Clicking on 'Save Data List' button, a Save Data List window pops
up. After entering the title for the Data List and clicking on Save,
the data list gets saved and a success message is displayed at the
bottom of the page.
1) After saving the Experiment, a success message is displayed at the
bottom of the page.
2) After clicking on the 'Experiment' tab, all the parent projects are
displayed.
3) Double clicking on any project shows experiments and sub projects
under it.
Verification Logic:

erification Logic:
f the user searches for geneconnect.domain.gene with a rule: Identifier Less Than 21. Then in "View Search Results" page:
ath map = Paths: Gene
ow, say the user clicks on Gene 4, then the
ath map = Paths: Gene -> Gene 4
ow, if the user clicks on the class, geneconnect.domain.Protein then path map becomes : Paths: Gene -> Gene 4 -> Protein
ow, if the user clicks on object, Protein 7, then the path becomes: Paths: Gene -> Gene 4 -> Protein -> Protein 7
Now, for eg., in the path map if the user clicks on Gene 4 then the system should navigate to the object, Gene 4, and display its description and "Related Data".

erification Logic:
ll the data that is available for a particular object in the database
hould get displayed once the user clicks on that object in the "View Search Results" page.
n the "Related Data" column all those which have bidirectional association with our class of interest are shown. If a unidirectional assocition from our class of interest to other classes exists, then all such classes also become part of the "Related Data" column.
owever, if a unidirectional association from other classes to our class of interest exists, then such classes do not become part of the "Related Data" column.
or "Inter Model Associations" all those classes are listed which have bidirectional assocaition between our class of interest and them.

Expected Output:

on "Search", the system returns results. On clicking on any of the
returned results, the system navigates to the "Add Limits" tab.
) In the "Add Limits" tab, a set of attributes with their
corresponding list of operators is displayed.
) Once the user adds a limit on the attribute, then that particular
category to which this attribute belongs, gets registered in the DAG
view.

clicking on "Next", the system navigates to the "Define Search
Results View" tab. Here the classes on which rule was set are
displayed alongwith their description.

tab.

the "Add Limits" tab are displayed.
) When the user opts for the "Apply Data List" option for the selected
elements then the system looks into the "Data List" for currently
selected element type and finds out what additional annotations are
added to the data list for that element type and fetches similar
annotations for the current selected element and adds it to the
data list.
Verification Logic:
For example:
uppose the data list contains following hierarchy
fe.genes
|
|-----gene1
|
|--chromosome1
|--unigene1
|
|---genbank accession
|
|---- gene2
|
|--- literature network genes
ow, suppose user is on summary result page of Genes and selects gene2, gene3, gene4 and clicks 'Apply Data List' button, for all the above selected genes (#2, #3, #4) the application should add corresponding chromosome, unigene, genbank accession and literature network genes in appropriate hierarchy in the data list. The result of this event on data list will be as shown below:
|
|-----gene1
|
|--chromosome1
|--unigene1
|
|---genbank accession
|
|---- gene2
|
|--- literature network genes
|
|--chromosome2
|--unigene2
|
|---genbank accession2
|
|---- gene3
|
|--- literature network genes
|
|--chromosome3
|--unigene3
|
|---genbank accession3
|
|---- gene4
|
|--- literature network genes
|
|--chromosome4
|--unigene4
|
|---genbank accession4

) Clicking on ">>", the system navigates to the next set of 5 pages.
) Clicking on "<", the system navigates to the previous page.
) Clicking on ">", the system navigates to the next page.
) On the first page the arrow links corresponding to previous set and
previous page will be disabled.
0) On the last page the arrow links corresponding to the next set and
next page will be disabled.

Test to ensure that a user can carry out a text based search against a category, and the system will return a set of results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1. Start the caB2B admin Application by opening the link.
. Select the Create category link from the Search data tab.
. Expand the Advance Search Option.
. Select the Text Option Button.
. Select the Category check box available.
. Type in the search term in the Search Box.

nput/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. These results will contain the search item as a part or whole in the
category name.
erification Logic:
The search item will be present as a substring, or as a whole in the category name.

 2008-03-31 2008-05-26 BOTH
v2.0 Admin Module Create Category Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against the attributes Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a concept code based search against attributes and the system will return a set of results.
Setup:
Procedure:
. Start the caB2B admin Application by opening the link.
. Select the Create category link from the Search data tab.
. Expand the Advance Search Option.
. Select the Concept code Option Button.
. Select the Attribute check box available.
. Type in the search term in the Search Box.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. In a concept code based search against a category, the system looks
for the concepts codes corresponding to the class name.
. The search term must match the concept code for 1 of the attributes of
the returned results.
Verification Logic:
The system searches for the search item (concept code) against the concept codes of the attributes, and it returns the categories that contains the search item in the list of the concept codes for attributes..
o in the results returned it is possible that we do not have any instance of the search item (object name corresponding to the concept code) in the category names. So in such cases, the results returned can be verified by checking for the entries in the database, where the search item will be present in the concept code corresponding to the attribute list of the returned categories.

v2.0 Admin Module Create Category Test to ensure that the user can enter multiple search items separated by space/s in the search field Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can search for multiple terms at one go by entering multiple search items in the search field delimited by space/s.
Setup:
Procedure:
1) Start the caB2B admin Application by opening the link.
) Select the Create category link from the Search data tab.
) Check the check box corresponding to either "Category" or "Attribute".
) Select the radio button corresponding to either "Text" or "Concept
Code".
) Enter multiple search items (eg : item1 item2) separated by space/s in
the search field.
) Click on search.
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of results.
. Some of the returned results will contain item1 as a part or whole in
the category name.
. Some of the returned results will contain item2 as a part or whole in
the category name.
Verification Logic:
If search items are separated by space/s the system considers each search item individually, and searches them against the category or attribute depending on which check box is selected.
mongst the search results returned some results would contain only item1 as a part or whole of the category name. Some search results would contain item2 as apart or whole of the category name.

v2.0 Admin Module Create Category Test to ensure that the user can carry out a text based search agaianst a class and attribute simultaneously Purpose:
Test to ensure that the user can carry out a text based search against the category and attributes simultaneously, and the system will return a set of search results.
Setup:
Procedure:
1) Start the caB2B admin Application by opening the link.
) Select the Create category link from the Search data tab.
) Check the check boxes corresponding to both "Category" and "Attribute".
) Select the radio button corresponding to "Text".
) Enter a search item in the search field.
) Click on "Search".
Input/Data:
Expected Output:
1. The system will return a set of search results.
. Amongst the set of search results returned, some results would contain
the search item as a part or whole of the category name. Some results
would not contain the search item in the category name.
Verification Logic:
While the system searches in the category and attribute list simultaneously, the category names that contain the search item as a part or whole are returned. The categories which contain the search item as a part or whole in its attribute list are also returned. These categories may not have the search item in its category name, so these results have to be verified by checking for the entry in the database.
